Tidy Tuesday: Plotting Geospatial Data in R

This notebook is intended to give you the basics of using the longitude and latitude data from the water dataset to get visualizations which involve maps. First, lets load the (large) dataset:

library(tidyverse)

water <- readr::read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/rfordatascience/tidytuesday/master/data/2021/2021-05-04/water.csv')

We will be using the maps library in R. If you have not installed this library yet, run

install.packages("maps")

Plotting the coordinate data is not a big deal! First, we need to load the map data, which is part of the maps library. We can then use the geom_polygon layer from ggplot() to produce a map.

library(maps)

world_map <- map_data("world")

world_map %>%
  ggplot(aes(long, lat, group = group)) +
  geom_polygon(fill = "white", color = "black") + 
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude")

Now, we can also use a geom_point() layer to add the coordinates from the water dataset, which are stored in the lon_deg and lat_deg columns. (Notice that I am not using a pipe %>% to feed in the dataset, since we are plotting using two different datasets and I was too lazy to merge them.)

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = world_map, aes(long, lat, group = group), fill = "white", color = "black") + 
  geom_point(data = water, aes(lon_deg, lat_deg), color = "blue") + 
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude")

Whoa! Something doesnt look right here and it turns out that it is the data itself! Some coordinates are correct, but others are way off in Antarctica! (You can confirm this by consulting the original data set.) It is a really good thing that we plotted this data- otherwise we might have used the lon_deg and lat_deg as predictors in a model. We are supposed to only be looking at African countries. How can we restrict our focus to only African countries?

#This pulls a dataset of country names, codes, continents, etc.
library(raster)
cc <- raster::ccodes()

#Pull the map data for the african countries only
africa_map <- map_data("world", regions = (cc %>%
                                         filter(continent == "Africa") %>%
                                         pull(NAME)
                                         )
                       )

#Now we can plot the data. I am using the filter() function to restrict the geom_point() layer to coordinates that make sense for africa.
ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = africa_map, aes(long, lat, group = group), fill = "white", color = "black") + 
  geom_point(data = (water %>%
                       filter(lon_deg > -50 & lon_deg < 60,
                              lat_deg > -40 & lat_deg < 30)
                       ), aes(lon_deg, lat_deg), color = "blue") + 
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude")
